I have been overly emotional because I just truly cannot believe this is happening. Just 6 years ago, I was completely overweight & hated myself. My life was unfulfilling and I cared about pretty much nothing. Now, I’ve built a life I’m incredibly proud of. I get to walk into my very own gym, where I get to watch people change their own life— and none of this would be possible without you guys. I’m so beyond grateful. Thank you, always 🫶

If you told the first girl that she’d own a gym in 6 years, she would’ve laughed in your face….

We’ve talked so much about the physical change in my transformation, but not a whole lot on the mental change.

From the way I handle stress, to the level of discipline I maintain, to my emotional intelligence & relationship dynamics — everything has improved. Once I started pouring into myself and actually showing up, my entire life slowly started to change. 

Now, 6 years later, it looks completely different. And that’s not an accident.

It’s not just about going to the gym and eating healthy food… It’s waking up everyday and following through with the commitments that you’ve made to yourself. It’s the consistent daily actions & routine that you build and follow. It’s making the overall decision to be better & proving to yourself that you will be.

Point is: when you stop making excuses & start actually putting in the work, EVERYTHING will change. Maybe not overnight, but it will happen. 

Nobody can do it for you. 

So, get to f*cking work 🫡

heaviest I’ve ever been 👉🏼 lightest I’ve ever been 👉🏼 starting my first growing phase.

My fitness journey started (2017) when I was overweight & the goal was to just be smaller. Once I lost 70lb, I was still stuck on that “smaller” goal for a while. I reached my leanest point in 2020 (middle photo) & knowing it wasn’t sustainable, I thought “ok, what’s next?”

I have flip-flopped between maintenance and mini-cuts over the last few years but have never committed to a building phase because the thought of it was so scary. I didn’t trust myself to gain weight in a healthy way & wasn’t sure I would be able to stay away from a “f*ck it” mentality and just pack the weight back on. Also, any time I felt a small amount of added fat anywhere around my stomach, my body image went down the drain & I felt like I was back in my old unhealthy body. That may sound dramatic, but it’s the best way I can explain it. 

Something changed over this summer, though, and I found a new itch to grow & approach a new big challenge. There’s something about welcoming uncharted territory while knowing you have the resources to face the obstacles that come up. So, while I know this bulk will bring new struggles & triggers, I’m excited to watch myself power through it. Nothing worth doing ever comes easy.

HERE’S TO GROWING & TAKING UP SPACE 💪🏼💥

I graduated high school at 15 & got my first job. 

I moved out on my own at 17. 

I worked 2-3 jobs at a time from 18-21. 

I started my first business at 22. 

I bought my first gym at 25 — these are the coordinates. 

A permanent reminder of how far I’ve come & how much more I can’t wait to accomplish. 

If you have a dream, no matter how wild, GO FOR IT. 

Stop talking yourself out of it before you even start — you’ll never know what you’re truly capable of until you believe in yourself & start working as hard as you possibly can.

New Years is around the corner, so cue the “new year, new me” mindset. 

But, what if this year you set yourself up to actually make lasting changes??

I had a few phases of trying to lose weight, but they were short lived when I didn’t see results. Eventually, I got sick & tired of the failed process & was craving a new life altogether. It wasn’t until I sat down & figured out what SUSTAINABLE changes I could incorporate into my life, that this process actually began.

It wasn’t heavily restricting my calories every single day, training 6x weekly, daily cardio, 10k steps, etc. What finally changed my life was filling my schedule with movement I liked, healthy foods I looked forward to, and fun activities in my free time that made me happier & motivated to want more. 

I stopped thinking “what do I have to do for x amount of time, to get the results I want” and started to live the new lifestyle I envisioned for myself. I would wake up excited to train, because it was so empowering to conquer something hard every day. These days compounded into weeks, then months, then years. 

Now here I am, almost 6 years later, thriving in my “new lifestyle”. I’ve had ebbs & flows with training & nutrition, but that’s all a part of the balance that creates success. It all comes down to consistency & sustainability. 

So, instead of creating strict resolutions that will probably fall off in a few months, I dare you to ask yourself: “what can I do in 2024 to build the LIFESTYLE I want?”

My cutting protocol 👇🏼

•I started January 2nd and plan to end right before we go to Cabo on March 10th, for a total of 9.5 weeks. 

•I have 2 small diet breaks scheduled — about every 3 weeks. they happen to fall on dates Brian & I are traveling, which is perfect bc I want to enjoy my time without being heavily restricted.

•Starting with my calories just under maintenance, then lowering after each diet break. Goal is to lower calories conservatively. I’d rather add more cardio than eat less lol but regardless there’s a balance. 

•Completing 20 mins 3x weekly on the stair master & will adjust as needed but won’t end anywhere crazy.

•Walking 3 miles on my (5) training days, 4 miles on my (1) active rest day & then having 1 full rest day. 

•Adding in a weekly group class on my active rest day. Yoga, pilates, etc. — something to get me out of my comfort zone.

•Prioritizing sleeping well, hydrating enough, and recovery practices (baths, massages, sauna, etc)

*what works for me won’t necessarily work for you. I’m just sharing what I will be doing for this cut as many of you have been asking*
